# Router-on-a-Stick

# Overview

The Corporate Office network uses the Router-on-a-Stick (RoaS) architecture to provide inter-VLAN routing.

Router-on-a-Stick is a method of routing traffic between multiple VLANs using a single physical router interface. 
Instead of dedicating one physical interface per VLAN, multiple logical subinterfaces are created on a single interface. 
Each subinterface acts as the default gateway for a specific VLAN.

This approach reduces hardware requirements while providing efficient communication between isolated VLANs.

# Why Router-on-a-Stick?

The Office network contains multiple VLANs that represent different departments.

Since VLANs are separate Layer 2 broadcast domains, devices in different VLANs cannot communicate through switching alone.

Router-on-a-Stick enables communication between these VLANs while maintaining logical network segmentation.

Benefits include:

- Efficient use of router interfaces
- Reduced hardware requirements
- Centralized inter-VLAN routing
- Easy scalability for additional VLANs
- Enterprise-standard implementation for small to medium-sized networks


# Network Topology

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Office Router \n GigabitEthernet0/0] --> | IEEE 802.1Q Trunk | B[Office Core Switch]
    
    B --> c[VLAN 10]
    B --> d[VLAN 20]
    B --> e[VLAN 30]
```

The connection between the Office Router and the Office Switch operates as an IEEE 802.1Q trunk, allowing multiple VLANs to share a single physical Ethernet link.

# Router Interface Design

The Office router uses one physical interface connected to the switch.

| Interface | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| GigabitEthernet0/0 | 802.1Q trunk to Office Switch |

This physical interface does **not** have an IP address assigned.

Instead, IP addresses are configured on logical subinterfaces.

# Router Subinterfaces

Each VLAN is assigned a dedicated router subinterface.

| Subinterface | VLAN | Purpose |
|--------------|------|---------|
| GigabitEthernet0/0.10 | VLAN 10 | Default Gateway |
| GigabitEthernet0/0.20 | VLAN 20 | Default Gateway |
| GigabitEthernet0/0.30 | VLAN 30 | Default Gateway |

Each subinterface performs Layer 3 routing for its associated VLAN.

# IEEE 802.1Q Encapsulation

Router-on-a-Stick relies on IEEE 802.1Q VLAN tagging.

When traffic leaves the switch over the trunk link, a VLAN tag is added to each Ethernet frame.

The router examines this VLAN tag and forwards the traffic to the corresponding subinterface.

This allows a single physical interface to process traffic for multiple VLANs simultaneously.

# Packet Flow

Example:

A workstation in VLAN 10 communicates with a workstation in VLAN 20.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[PC VLAN 10] 

    A --> B[Office Switch] --> |802.1Q Trunk| C[Office Router] 
    C --> | Routes Packet | D[Office Switch]

    D --> E[PC VLAN 20]
```

Traffic is forwarded to the router, routed between VLANs, and returned to the switch for delivery to the destination VLAN.

# Default Gateways

Each VLAN uses the router subinterface as its default gateway.

| VLAN | Default Gateway |
|------|-----------------|
| VLAN 10 | 192.168.1.1 |
| VLAN 20 | 192.168.1.65 |
| VLAN 30 | 192.168.1.129 |

All devices within a VLAN forward traffic destined for another network to their respective default gateway.

# Advantages

The current implementation provides several advantages:

- Efficient utilization of router interfaces
- Centralized Layer 3 routing
- Logical network segmentation
- Reduced hardware cost
- Simplified administration
- Support for future network expansion

# Current Implementation

The Office network currently implements:

- One Cisco 2911 Router
- One IEEE 802.1Q trunk
- Three router subinterfaces
- Three VLANs
- Inter-VLAN communication
- DHCP support for each VLAN

The implementation successfully allows communication between different VLANs while maintaining logical separation at Layer 2.

# Current Limitations

The current Router-on-a-Stick implementation allows unrestricted communication between VLANs.

Although this is suitable for demonstrating inter-VLAN routing, production enterprise networks typically enforce security policies between departments.

Future versions of this project will implement:

- Extended Access Control Lists (ACLs)
- Network Address Translation (NAT/PAT)
- Dynamic routing (OSPF)
- Firewall integration

These enhancements will improve security while maintaining the existing routing architecture.

# Summary

Router-on-a-Stick provides the Layer 3 functionality required for communication between multiple Office VLANs using a single physical router interface.

The design minimizes hardware requirements while maintaining scalability and serving as the foundation for future enterprise networking features such as ACLs, NAT, and dynamic routing.